    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>The trolley problem has a correct answer. Philosophy departments just don't like saying so.</p>
  <p>Five people on the tracks. One person on the side track. A lever in front of you. Pull it, and one dies instead of five. Every intro ethics class treats this as an open question, a Rorschach test for your moral framework. Professors present the dilemma, students debate, the lecture ends with a shrug dressed up as intellectual humility: "There's no right answer."</p>
  <p>Except 68% of professional philosophers say pull the lever. Around 90% of survey respondents agree. When Michael Stevens ran the first realistic version of the experiment in 2017, with real-looking footage and real-seeming stakes, five of seven participants froze. That split is revealing. In the abstract, people know the answer. Facing the lever, they can't execute it.</p>
  <p>The gap between those two findings is the actual lesson. The trolley problem doesn't expose a genuine moral paradox. It exposes the distance between moral reasoning and moral nerve.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-arithmetic-nobody-wants-to-own" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Arithmetic Nobody Wants to Own</h2>
  <p>Strip the problem to its frame and the math is almost offensively simple. One death or five. Every additional variable people introduce ("What if the one person is a doctor?" "What if the five are criminals?") is an attempt to escape the scenario's constraints, not engage with them. The thought experiment specifies five strangers, one stranger, no other information. Given those terms, the person who refuses to pull the lever has chosen, through inaction, to let four additional people die. That is not neutrality. It is a decision with a body count.</p>
  <p>The instinct to do nothing feels principled. It rests on what philosophers call the acts/omissions distinction: the idea that killing someone is morally different from letting someone die. Plausible in the abstract. Less so under pressure. A doctor who could save a patient with a routine intervention but declines because "I didn't cause the illness" has not preserved his moral record. He has found a more sophisticated way to fail.</p>
</section>

<section id="why-it-feels-hard" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why It Feels Hard</h2>
  <p>The discomfort is real, but its source is less noble than it feels. Psychologists have documented that cognitive overload, reminders of death, and emotional priming all push people toward inaction in trolley scenarios. People with damage to the ventromedial prefrontal cortex, the brain region that processes emotional responses, are <em>more</em> likely to pull the lever. What many people experience as moral gravity turns out to be, at least in part, emotional friction. The gut says don't intervene. The gut is not a moral philosopher.</p>
  <p>A frequently cited study found that people who chose the utilitarian option scored higher on measures of psychopathy. This gets deployed as evidence that saving more lives is somehow cold-blooded. The actual finding is narrower: people willing to override emotional discomfort in favor of a better outcome share one trait with people who lack empathy altogether. Reduced empathic distress. Surgeons share it too. So do paramedics. Acting under moral pressure is not pathology. It is a job requirement for anyone society trusts with serious decisions.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-fat-man-and-other-escape-hatches" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Fat Man and Other Escape Hatches</h2>
  <p>Critics of the utilitarian answer love the fat man variant. Same setup, but instead of pulling a lever, you push a large man off a bridge to stop the trolley. Most people refuse. Philosophers treat this as proof that pure consequentialism fails, that the <em>means</em> matter, not just the outcome.</p>
  <p>They're right. The means do matter. But the fat man variant doesn't disprove the answer to the original problem. It proves something different: that using a person's body as a physical instrument crosses a moral line the lever does not. The lever redirects a threat. Pushing someone off a bridge converts a bystander into a tool. Kant wasn't wrong about everything; treating people as mere means is a real boundary. The organ-harvesting variant, where you kill one healthy patient to distribute his organs to five, makes the same point with sharper teeth.</p>
  <p>None of which changes the lever case. In the standard scenario, you are not using the one person as an instrument. You are redirecting an existing threat. The one person's death is a foreseeable side effect, not the mechanism of rescue. The doctrine of double effect, a principle even Catholic moral theology endorses, permits exactly this distinction.</p>
  <p>The fat man is a different problem with a potentially different answer. Treating it as a rebuttal of the original is like arguing that because some surgeries are unethical, surgery itself is suspect.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-the-no-right-answer-framing-protects" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the "No Right Answer" Framing Protects</h2>
  <p>Treating the trolley problem as an unsolvable paradox flatters our discomfort but fails the people on the tracks. It is a framework built for seminar rooms, where the cost of moral indecision is a lively class discussion rather than four unnecessary deaths.</p>
  <p>Philippa Foot, who invented the scenario in 1967, designed it as an argument <em>against</em> utilitarianism. Judith Jarvis Thomson, who gave the problem its name and spent decades analyzing it, eventually reversed course in 2008 and argued that diverting the trolley is not permissible after all. Most ethicists found her reversal unpersuasive. The consensus held. The thought experiment Foot designed to expose consequentialism's limits ended up demonstrating its core appeal: that in constrained life-or-death decisions, with no additional information, most humans and most trained philosophers arrive at the consequentialist answer anyway.</p>
  <p>The trolley problem has a correct answer. Pull the lever. Save four lives. The guilt is the price of seriousness.</p>
</section>
